@node "System" "QWKGate System requirement"
@{b}-- System Requirement --@{ub}


If you want to use QWKGate and QWKGate_Prefs you must at least have
Kickstart 2.0 or higher.

From part of this it should work at any Amiga. If not send a message to
@{"Richard" link "Programmer" 0} or @{"Robert" link "Author_Info" 0}.
@endnode

@node "Installation" "Installation of QWKGate"
@{b}-- Installation --@{ub}


@{b}@{u}QWKGate :@{ub}@{uu}

The installation of QWKGate is easy, simply copy the program QWKGate in your
cli path (your C-directory or Tools-directory, etc.)

After you've installed QWKGate you will have to make a config-file, see
@{"configuration" link "Configuration" 0} or the example @{"DIVO.BBS" link "DIVO.BBS" 0} config file.


@{b}@{u}QWKGate_Prefs :@{ub}@{uu}

QWKGate_Prefs can be placed in any directory. Preferably in the (usual)
Pref: directory or in the MAIL: directory of the POINT program.
@endnode

@node "Configuration" "The configuration of QWKGate"
@{b}-- Configuration --@{ub}

QWKGate is configuered by a .BBS file. This is a normal ascii file which can
be made with programs such as Edit, CED, etc. (each program which can save
in ascii- format). These configuration files can be recognized by the .BBS
extension. The standard configuration of QWKGate is MAIL:QWKGATE.BBS. If
this doesn't exist QWKgate will look for the file MAIL:DIVO.BBS.

It is for the begining user not easy to use an ascii editor to make a .BBS
prefs file. I made plans to work on a prefs editor. With this program you
should easily make a prefs file, by clicking at the options with the
mouse-button. This idea was picked up by Robert Guezen, who started to work
at the prefs editor. The program QWKGate_Prefs is copyright 1995 by R.
Geuzen and is part of this release.

The configuration file exist out of textlines. At each textline you can only
get one option. At this moment the working of the configuration file isn't
very intelligent, but it works as long as you follow the next rules:

A textline can be found in the .BBS files as:

 > an empty line will be skipped

 > a line starting with ; is a comment line and will skipped by QWKGate,
see
   the next example:

; this is a comment line

 > a line starting with a command, followed by one or more spaces and the
   vallue of the instruction which is mentioned. Commands aren't case
   sensitive, see the next example:

DOWNLOAD    DH0:COMMS/DOWNLOAD

or

DOWNLOAD       DH0:COMMS DIRECTORY/DOWNLOAD

or

download dh0:comms/download

To make sure that you also can give text vallues begining with a space, the
first \\ off a vallue will be recognized as the sign for the begining of the
vallue, this sounds a bit confusing, but is works as folowed:

ORIGIN_TEXT \ * Origin:

gives as vallue ' * Origin: '

 > a textline starting with a command only. These are the socalled tags,
which
   starts an option. See the example

AREA_NAMES_TO_UPPER

As you can see you can put spaces in the lines, without putting them between
commas.

The configuration options can be divided into the next groups:

 - @{"Standard options" link "config_standard_options" 0}      download-,  upload directory, inbound, etc.

 - @{"QWK to FIDO options" link "config_qwk2fido" 0}   userarea, userarea_naam, userkill, etc.

 - @{"FIDO to QWK options" link "config_fido2qwk" 0}   origin_change, origin_kill, etc.


See for example @{"DIVO.BBS" link "DIVO.BBS" 0}
@endnode

@node "config_standard_options" "Configuration Standard options"
@{b}-- Configuration standard commands --@{ub}

@{u}BBSID <name>@{uu}

  With this command you can indicate the BBSID of the QWK packet wich
  you want to convert. This is always the file name of the part which 
  you have become, without the QWK extension.
  
  At the AMBBS you can get the part DIVO.QWK, so you have the set the
  BBSID as DIVO. See the example:
 
  @{i}BBSID DIVO@{ui}


@{u}DOWNLOAD <DIRECTORY>@{uu}

  With this command you can indicate the download directory which is used
  for downloading the QWK packets from the BBS. See the example:
 
  @{i}DOWNLOAD DH0:COMMS/DOWNLOAD@{ui}


@{u}UPLOAD <DIRECTORY>@{uu}

  With this command you can indicate the upload directory which is used to
  put the reply packet into. You then can upload these to the BBS. See the
  example:
  
  @{i}UPLOAD DH0:COMMS/UPLOAD@{ui}


@{u}INBOUND <DIRECTORY>@{uu}

  This is the directory where the fidopacket can be generated which is
  converted from the QWK packet. It then can be used to read it in your
  mail packet. This directory is usualy called MAIL:INBOUND. See the
  example:
 
  @{i}INBOUND MAIL:INBOUND@{ui}


@{u}OUTBOUND <DIRECTORY>@{uu}

  This is the directory where the fidopacket with the replies and the
  own messages wil be put by the mail packet. QWKGate will look into
  this directory to convert to a QWK reply packet. See the example:
 
  @{i}OUTBOUND MAIL:OUTBOUND@{ui}


@{u}TEMP <DIRECTORY>@{uu}

  This directory is used by QWKGate to unpack and generated several
  temporary data.
  BE WARE! This directory won't automaticly be installed by QWKGate, but
  it will be used by it. See the example:

  @{i}TEMP MAIL:TEMP@{ui}


@{u}BBS_NODE <NODE>@{uu}

  This will be used for the handling of the mail by the mail packet.
  You will have to choose for the NODE which won't be used in other areas.
  This node number is the virtual node number of the BBS were you get your
  mail from. The keyword-node stand for 3- as well as 4-dimensial adresses:
  
  @{i}BBS_NODE 99:999/999.0    of BBS_NODE 99:999/999@{ui}


@{u}POINT_NODE <NODE>@{uu}

  This equals the BBS_NODE command, but it is the node number which is used
  for the exporting and importing of the messages. See the example: 
 
  @{i}POINT_NODE 99:999/999.9@{ui}


@{u}NETMAIL_AREA <AREA_NAAM>@{uu}

  The QWK system hasn't got a standard  area which is used for private
  messages. Usualy the area is called E-MAIL of EMAIL, but that isn't a
  standard. To use an areas (or forum) for netmail you can use this option.
  the forum with the AREA_NAME will be seen as the area for private
  messages.  See the example:
 
  @{i}NETMAIL_AREA EMAIL@{ui}


@{u}CONVERT_NETMAIL@{uu}

  This command does exactly the same as the NETMAIL_AREA, but will be seen
  as the same area as E-MAIL. See the example.

  @{i}CONVERT_NETMAIL@{ui}


@{u}LHA_UNPACK <COMMAND>@{uu}

  This command line will be used for unpacking the LHA data. The default 
  value is C:lha -r e, see the example: 
 
  @{i}LHA_UNPACK C:lha -r e@{ui}


@{u}ZIP_UNPACK <COMMAND>@{uu}

  This command line will be used for unpacking the ZIP data. The default 
  value is C:unzip -o, see the example: 
 
  @{i}ZIP_UNPACK C:unzip -o@{ui}
@endnode

@node "config_qwk2fido" "Configuratie QWK naar FIDO opties"
@{b}-- Configuration QWK to FIDO commands --@{ub}

@{u}USERAREA_NAME <AREA_NAME>@{uu}

  One disadvantage of QWK mail is that you will get your own messages back.
  To make sure that you won't read the same messages twice in the same
area,
  you can use this option to make an area in were you own messages will be
  transferred to. You can give it any AREA_NAME you like, see the example:

  @{i}USERAREA_NAME RICHARD RETURN@{ui}


@{u}USERAREA@{uu}

  This option does the same as USERAREA_NAME, but it will use the standard
  area name 'BACK_ANSWER', see the example:

  @{i}USERAREA@{ui}


@{u}USERKILL@{uu}

  This option also involves the returning of your own messages. If you use
  this option the returning messages will be killed, so you won't see them.

  @{i}USERKILL@{ui}


@{u}AREA_NAMES_TO_UPPER@{uu}

  This option converts the names of the areas to uppercase, see the
example.

  @{i}AREA_NAMES_TO_UPPER@{ui}


@{u}DONT_UNPACK_QWK@{uu}

  If you use this option the QWK packet won't be unpacked. If you use this
  option you will have to make sure that the next files will be in your
  TEMP directory: control.dat and messages.dat. These will be used for 
  the converting of the QWK packets. See the example:

  @{i}DONT_UNPACK_QWK@{ui}


@{u}DELETE_QWK_PACKET@{uu}

  This option will delete the downloaded QWK packets after they are
transferred
  to a fido packet. See the example:
 
  @{i}DELETE_QWK_PACKET@{ui}
@endnode

@node "config_fido2qwk" "Configuration FIDO to QWK options"
@{b}-- Configuration FIDO to QWK command's --@{ub}

@{u}ORIGIN_TEXT <TEXT>@{uu}

  With this command you can select The text which is used for the origin
  text. It is used for converting or deleting of the origin text, default
  ' * Origin:'. See the example.
 
  @{i}ORIGIN_TEXT \ * Origin:@{ui}


@{u}ORIGIN_CHANGE@{uu}

  With this command you can select the origin text which will be converted
  to a tagline. It has to start with 3 dots. See example.

  @{i}ORIGIN_CHANGE@{ui}


@{u}ORIGIN_KILL@{uu}

  With this command you can delete the Origin line of a message, see
example.
 
  @{i}ORIGIN_KILL@{ui}


@{u}QWK_PACK <COMMAND>@{uu}

  This command is used to pack your QWK packet. The default value is C:zip
-jrk,
  see example.
 
  @{i}QWK_PACK C:zip -jkr@{ui}


@{u}SIGNOFF_MAILER_NAME <NAME>@{uu}

  Almost all mail programs, like Spot or April, wil put their name at the
and
  of the messages. Spot puts at the end of a message '--- Spot 1.x #user'
  and April puts "--- April Vxxx' at the end. By using SIGNOFF_MAILER_NAME
  you can let QWKGate add his name to this. You wil get '--- Spot 1.x #user
  & QWKGate x.xxx'. See example:

  @{i}SIGNOFF_MAILER_NAME --- April@{ui}


@{u}SIGNOFF_AFTER_MAILER@{uu}

  This function corresponds to SIGNOFF_MAILER_NAME but the default value is
the
  Spot mailer.

  @{i}SIGNOFF_AFTER_MAILER@{ui}


@{u}SIGNOFF_ORIGIN@{uu}

  This is a mix of ORIGIN_CHANGE and SIGNOFF_MAILER_NAME. If you choose
  this option the origin line will be converted to a line which starts
  with  ' * QWKGate version | Origin line', see example:

  @{i}SIGNOFF_ORIGIN@{ui}


@{u}ADD_TO_OLD_REPLY@{uu}

  This option makes sure that new messages will be add to an old QWK reply,
  so you can use the FIDO2QWK option several times. This option is useful
  if you can't connect with your BBS and you want to add a message to
  your replies. @{b}BE WARE: You have to make sure that the QWK REPLY PACKET
  will be deleted after uploading@{ub}. See example:

  @{i}ADD_TO_OLD_REPLY@{ui}


@{u}WRITER_CHECK@{uu}

  This option controles, during conversion of a FIDO packet to a QWK REPLY
  packet, of the name of the name of the sender corresponds with the name
of
  the user, as used in the original QWK packet. If the names don't
correspond
  a requester wil appear with the question iff you want to converd this
message.  

  @{i}WRITER_CHECK@{ui}


@{u}DONT_UNPACK_QWK@{uu}

  This option makes sure that the QWK REPLY packet won't be unpacked, see
example:

  @{i}DONT_UNPACK_QWK@{ui}
@endnode

@node "QWK2FIDO" "QWK to FIDO"
@{b}-- Converting QWK to FIDO --@{ub}

The following option will be used to convert a QWK packet to FIDO packet:

QWKGate QWK2FIDO [@{"QUIET" link "QUIET" 0}] [BBS_PREFS_FILE]

If you don't fill in the BBS_PREFS_FILE the default value which will be used
is MAIL:QWKGATE.BBS and if this doesn't exist MAIL:DIVO.BBS

And thats it. Of course you must make the BBS_PREFS_FILE. See for this
@{"configuration" link "Configuration" 0} or QWKGate_Prefs.
@endnode

@node "FIDO2QWK" "FIDO to QWK"
@{b}-- Converting FIDO to QWK --@{ub}

The following option will be used to convert a FIDO packet to a QWK packet:

QWKGate FIDO2QWK [@{"QUIET" link "QUIET" 0}] [BBS_PREFS_FILE]

If you don't fill in the BBS_PREFS_FILE the default value which will be used
is MAIL:QWKGATE.BBS and if this doesn't exist MAIL:DIVO.BBS

And thats it. Of course you must make the BBS_PREFS_FILE. See for this
@{"configuration" link "Configuration" 0} or QWKGate_Prefs.
@endnode

@node "QUIET" "QWKGate in QUIET mode"
@{b}-- QWKGate in QUIETMODE --@{ub}

QWKGate can also be used in a mode which only give error-requesters
(errors). For this you can use the QUIET option at the startup line, so:

  @{i}QWKGate FIDO2QWK QUIET MAIL:DIVO.BBS@{ui}

or

  @{i}QWKGate QWK2FIDO QUIET MAIL:DIVO.BBS@{ui}

This option makes sure that QWKGate "shuts op his mouth". BE WARE: The
programs which are used by QWKGate can put text to the screen, therefore you
can configure these programs so they won't text to the screen,

For this I have the following option in my .BBS config file:

  LHA_UNPACK C:lha -q -r e
  ZIP_UNPACK C:unzip -qq -o

  QWK_PACK   C:zip -jkrq
@endnode

@node "History" "The history of QWKGate"
@{b}-- History --@{ub}


@{b}@{u}QWKGate :@{ub}@{uu}

Okay, This is the history of QWKGate. It isn't big yet, but still groing.

- versions earlier then <0.3 internal versions

- version 0.3 first beta release

- version 0.31 - version 0.38 following beta releases
  some new options and some enforcer hits solved

- version 0.7 first public beta release specialy made for Amiga Magazine
BBS
  (the Netherlands)

- version 0.701 - 0.724 internal versions for the construction of the local
  support and autoreply function

- version 0.725 closed beta version for the official  beta testers

- version 1.0 first official release


@{b}@{u}QWKGate_Prefs :@{ub}@{uu}

0.7  - first beta release specialy made for Amiga Magazine BBS (the
Netherlands) 

0.71 - major bugs in use with OS 2.04/V37 recovered, distribution only
       via the Amiga Magazine BBS

1.0  - first official release
       Uses the ReqTools v38 requesters

For further update I'm depending on the users for suggestions and
bug-reports. You can send then to @{" Richard " link "Programmer" 0} or @{" Robert " alink "Author_Info" 0}
@endnode

